# Ecosystem analyzer (local run)

Goal: run ecosystem-analyzer locally for a single project and collect the JSON output, using a local ty repo/worktree.

## Inputs to gather
- Project name (e.g., scipy)

The remaining inputs are derived automatically from the current jj worktree:
- Commit to test (via `jj commit-id`)
- Path to the ty repo (via `jj git root --ignore-working-copy`)
- Output JSON path (use /tmp)

## Commands
1. Get jj git store path (jj worktree):
   ```sh
   jj git root --ignore-working-copy
   ```

2. Get commit ID:
   - Current commit:
     ```sh
     jj commit-id -r @
     ```
   - Main branch commit:
     ```sh
     jj commit-id -r main@origin
     ```

3. Run ecosystem-analyzer (no-project to avoid building the repo as a Python package):
   ```sh
   uv run --no-project \
     --with git+https://github.com/astral-sh/ecosystem-analyzer \
     ecosystem-analyzer \
     --repository <path-to-ty-repo-or-jj-git-store> \
     run \
     --project-name <project> \
     --commit <commit> \
     --profile profiling \
     -o /tmp/<project>-ecosystem.json
   ```

4. Read timing from the output JSON:
   ```sh
   rg -n "time_s" /tmp/<project>-ecosystem.json | tail -n 5
   ```

## Notes
- Assumes execution from a jj worktree. If using a git worktree, update the repo-path steps.
- The `--repository` option is a global option and must appear before `run`.
- For jj worktrees, use the git store path from `jj git root --ignore-working-copy`.
- If you hit cache-related errors, clear the ecosystem-analyzer cache and re-run.
- First run may recompile ty; a second run gives a better steady-state timing.
